involve the school. your child's school can provide resources & accommodations. this can help to keep your child engaged during an episode of depression or mania, which can boost self-esteem & academic performance.

support self-esteem. poor self-esteem is common in depression & reactions to a child's manic symptoms can cause feelings of disapproval. use praise freely but sincerely. your child can benefit from this encouragement.

make sleep a priority. getting enough sleep is an important part of recovery for bipolar disorder. poor sleep can also be a symptom of depression. be creative in helping your child with regular bedtimes and wake times.

talk about the disorder. talking helps your child to better understand depression and mania, that the disorder isn't their fault, and that with treatment it gets better. it also helps to build understanding among family.
